2. Water as a Universal Solvent
Water is called the "universal solvent" because it dissolves more substances than any other liquid. This
property arises directly from its unique molecular structure. Understanding water's chemistry is fundamental to all
environmental processes – nutrient cycling, toxicant transport, aquatic life support.
2.1 Molecular Structure of Water
Water Molecule Structure
• Molecular formula: HnO; Molecular weight: 18 g/mol
• Bond angle: 104.5° (not 180° – bent/angular shape due to 2 lone pairs on O)
• O–H bond length: 0.096 nm (very short = strong bond)
• Electronegativity of O (3.44) >> H (2.20) ® O is dn, H is dn (partial charges)
• This charge separation = polar covalent molecule with a permanent dipole moment (1.85 Debye)
• Result: water molecules attract each other and attract ions/polar solutes via electrostatic forces
2.2 Hydrogen Bonding – The Key to Water's Properties
Each water molecule can form up to 4 hydrogen bonds – 2 as donor (H) and 2 as acceptor (lone pairs on O). A
hydrogen bond is an electrostatic attraction between dn H of one molecule and dn O of another. Energy: 20–25
kJ/mol (weaker than covalent bonds ~400 kJ/mol, but enormously important collectively).
