2.5 Dielectric Constant and Ion Dissolution
The dielectric constant (e) of water is 80 – exceptionally high. This means water reduces the electrostatic
attraction between oppositely charged ions by a factor of 80 compared to vacuum. Formula: F = qnqn / (4pene
r²). High e ® ions in water attract each other with 1/80th the force ® easily separated ® dissolve readily. This is
why seawater contains so many dissolved salts.
n EXAM TIP: Water's bond angle = 104.5°; dipole moment = 1.85 D; dielectric constant = 80; density
maximum = 4°C; specific heat = 4186 J/kg·K. "Like dissolves like" – polar/ionic in water; non-polar in organic
solvents. Self-ionisation: HnO n Hn + OHn; Kw = 1×10n¹n at 25°C; pH + pOH = 14.
