3.3 DO Measurement – Winkler (Iodometric) Method
Winkler Method – Steps
Step 1 (Fixation): MnSOn + KOH/KI added to sample ® MnOn precipitate forms (fixes On)
Chemical: Mn²n + 2OHn ® Mn(OH)n; Mn(OH)n + ½On ® MnO(OH)n (brown ppt)
Step 2 (Acidification): HnSOn added ® MnO(OH)n + In ® In released (equivalent to On)
Chemical: MnO(OH)n + 2In + 4Hn ® Mn²n + In + 3HnO
Step 3 (Titration): In titrated against NanSnOn with starch indicator (blue ® colourless)
Chemical: In + 2NanSnOn ® 2NaI + NanSnOn
Calculation: 1 mL of 0.025 N NanSnOn = 0.2 mg On/L (for 200 mL sample)
Interferences: Nitrite (oxidises In ® false high DO) ® add azide modification (NaNn).
3.4 The DO Sag Curve (Streeter–Phelps Equation)
When organic waste is discharged into a river, DO drops as microbes consume it (BOD), then recovers as
reaeration occurs. The resulting curve is called the DO Sag Curve. It was mathematically described by Streeter
and Phelps (1925).
