4. Biochemical Oxygen Demand (BOD)
Biochemical Oxygen Demand (BOD) is the amount of dissolved oxygen consumed by biological organisms
(primarily bacteria) when decomposing organic matter in a given water sample at a specified temperature over a
specified time period. It is the standard measure of organic pollution in water.
4.1 BOD Test (Standard BODn Test)
Standard BODn Test Procedure
Conditions: 20°C in the dark for 5 days (Standard)
Sample preparation: Dilute sample with DO-saturated dilution water (to prevent On depletion too fast)
Seed: Add microbial seed (domestic sewage or acclimatised culture)
Measure: Initial DOn (Day 0) and Final DOn (Day 5)
Formula: BODn = (DOn - DOn) × Dilution Factor
Example: DOn = 9 mg/L; DOn = 3 mg/L; Dilution = 1:10 (100 mL sample in 1000 mL) BODn = (9-3) × 10 = 60 mg/L
Key requirements: DOn > 2 mg/L AND final DOn > 1 mg/L (otherwise re-dilute)
4.2 First-Order BOD Kinetics
BOD Exertion Equation (First-Order)
y_t = L_0 × (1 - e^(-k_d × t))
Where:
y_t = BOD exerted at time t (mg/L) = oxygen consumed by time t
L_0 = Ultimate BOD (L_u) = total oxygen demand if given infinite time (mg/L)
k_d = BOD rate constant (dayn¹) at 20°C; typical range 0.05–0.30 dayn¹
t = time (days)
Remaining BOD at time t: L_t = L_0 × e^(-k_d × t)
BODn = L_0 × (1 - e^(-5k_d)); for k_d=0.23/day: BODn » 0.68 × L_0 (i.e., 68% of L_0)
