5. Chemical Oxygen Demand (COD)
Chemical Oxygen Demand (COD) is the amount of oxygen required to chemically oxidise ALL organic matter
(and some inorganic reducing agents) in a water sample using a strong chemical oxidant under acidic conditions.
COD > BOD always, because COD oxidises even non-biodegradable compounds that BOD cannot measure.
5.1 COD Test – Dichromate Reflux Method
Standard COD Test (Open Reflux Method – IS 3025)
Oxidant: Potassium dichromate (KnCrnOn) in HnSOn (strong acid, hot conditions)
Catalyst: AgnSOn (silver sulphate) to oxidise short-chain fatty acids
Masking agent: HgSOn to remove Cln interference (Cln can falsely increase COD)
Conditions: 2-hour reflux at 150°C
Reaction: Organic matter + CrnOn²n ® COn + HnO + Cr³n (green)
Titration: Excess CrnOn²n back-titrated with FAS (ferrous ammonium sulphate) Indicator: Ferroin
(colour change: blue-green ® reddish-brown)
Formula: COD (mg/L) = [(A-B) × M × 8000] / V_sample where A = FAS for blank; B = FAS for sample; M = molarity of
FAS
5.2 COD Chemistry
The dichromate oxidation can be generalised as:
COD Stoichiometry
CnHnOn + CrnOn²n ® COn + HnO + Cr³n
For glucose: CnHnnOn + 6On ® 6COn + 6HnO ThCOD = 1.067 g On/g glucose (= ThOD)
Equivalence factor: 1 equivalent of CrnOn²n = 8 g of On
Substances measured by COD but NOT by BOD: lignin, cellulose (partial), benzene, toluene, pesticides
(non-biodegradable organics), some inorganics (Fe²n, S²n, NOnn)
